WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.040 --> 00:00:06.290
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.290 --> 00:00:07.590
&gt;&gt; Leigh Haber: I'm Leigh Haber.

00:00:07.590 --> 00:00:10.270
I'm Books Editor of
O, The Oprah Magazine.

00:00:10.270 --> 00:00:13.190
And I have the great honor
of being the moderator

00:00:13.190 --> 00:00:19.710
of this incredible pair of authors
who are very, very similar writers.

00:00:19.710 --> 00:00:21.920
That's what we were
just talking about.

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:28.190
Jacqueline Woodson whose
new book, Another Brooklyn,

00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:31.830
came out recently to rave reviews.

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:37.360
And Jay McInerney whose new
book Bright, Precious Days,

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:40.960
is also getting stellar coverage.

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:45.680
I read an interesting piece in the
New Yorker that you all might want

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:51.770
to look at, a really good
piece on Jay and his history.

00:00:51.770 --> 00:00:55.460
So what I want to start
talking about is

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:59.810
like why did the National
Books Festival pair you guys?

00:00:59.810 --> 00:01:03.390
It's like not exactly a no brainer.

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:05.150
But there is the New York thing.

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:07.430
&gt;&gt; Jay McInerney: We do
both write about New York.

00:01:07.430 --> 00:01:08.730
&gt;&gt; Leigh: That's right.

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:12.830 position:56%
So I'm guessing that was the thread.

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:17.840
So, Jackie, I'm going
to start with you.

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:19.710
You write about a New
York that's very different

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:23.240
from the one Jay writes about
in his trilogy and in this book.

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:29.670
Another Brooklyn, what does the
title Another Brooklyn suggest

00:01:29.670 --> 00:01:30.970
to you?

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:32.270
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline Woodson: Well,

00:01:32.270 --> 00:01:34.250
one thing it's definitely
from Jay's Manhattan.

00:01:34.250 --> 00:01:36.110
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Or the Brooklyn of today.

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:39.850
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline: Of the
Brooklyn -- yeah, definitely --

00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:41.150
&gt;&gt; Jay: Or Park Slope.

00:01:41.150 --> 00:01:42.450
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline: Or Park Slope.

00:01:42.450 --> 00:01:43.750
Well, Park Slope is its
own Another Brooklyn.

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:48.390 position:56%
So I'm writing about a Brooklyn that
no longer exists, a neighborhood

00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:50.800
that no longer exists as
it existed back in the day.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:55.350
And that's one of the
threads of the title.

00:01:55.350 --> 00:01:59.230
The other is, of course, the
girls wanting to find a way out of

00:01:59.230 --> 00:02:00.920
that Brooklyn and the
many people trying

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:02.650
to find a way out of that Brooklyn.

00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:08.060
It's also about all the different
lives that are being lived.

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:10.170
And so it has a lot of layers.

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:13.080
But really I wanted to put
Bushwick on the page in a way

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:15.570
that I think can easily
be forgotten.

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:19.320
I think a lot of times when
neighborhoods get, quote unquote,

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:22.680
discovered people forget
the history.

00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:26.400
And that it had been a neighborhood
where people were thriving.

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:27.990 position:56%
My daughter just started high school

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:29.670
at a high school called
Beacon in Manhattan.

00:02:29.670 --> 00:02:31.810 position:56%
And she came home and she was so mad

00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:34.220
because she said her
social studies teacher said,

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:38.920
I lived in Bed-Stuy before
it was safe for anybody.

00:02:38.920 --> 00:02:41.160
I'm like did you respond?

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:45.490
But just that idea that a
place where people of color are

00:02:45.490 --> 00:02:51.840 position:56%
where underserved people lived would
be considered a place that's not

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:56.010
inhabited because the people
living in it are not seen.

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.510
&gt;&gt; Leigh: And you are romantic
about Brooklyn in a way,

00:02:58.510 --> 00:02:59.810
the Brooklyn of that day.

00:02:59.810 --> 00:03:01.110
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline: Uh-huh.

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:02.410
&gt;&gt; Leigh: And that's something
I think you share with Jay.

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:05.190
Jay is very romantic
about Manhattan,

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:08.710
the Manhattan of the 80s,
the Manhattan of today.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.270
So would you agree
with that assessment?

00:03:11.270 --> 00:03:16.500
&gt;&gt; Jay: Well, yeah, I
still love Manhattan.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:25.030
But I think I have a -- in the
book the characters have a certain

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:30.480
nostalgia for the New York of their
20s which is the 80s basically.

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:34.440
And my wife gives me a very
hard time for being nostalgic

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.580
about a period when, you know,

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:40.620
when one's apartment was
constantly broken into

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:43.990
and there was a heroin epidemic,
when there was crack vials popping

00:03:43.990 --> 00:03:50.130 position:56%
under foot like acorns in the forest
and graffiti covered every surface.

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:55.530
But, you know, it was a very
creative time in New York.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:04:01.190
And also Manhattan hadn't
been thoroughly gentrified

00:04:01.190 --> 00:04:03.520
at that point which I think --

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:05.140
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Yeah, it's hard to
remember that, but you're right.

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:09.720
&gt;&gt; Jay: Yeah, which was
in some ways a good thing.

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:12.060
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Well, I asked
Jackie about her title.

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:18.370
And I'm interested in your love
for the word bright, Bright Lights,

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:23.440
Big City, the previous novel
that starts the trilogy

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:24.740
and now this one [inaudible].

00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:30.310
&gt;&gt; Leigh: I know it's become
a tick on my part I think.

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:35.400
It's funny I came up with this
title, and for me it was kind

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:39.930
of a mash up of me and Yeats.

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:43.550
For some reason I actually
thought that Yeats had this phrase

00:04:43.550 --> 00:04:47.200
in his poetry, and it
turns out he doesn't.

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:52.060
But by the time I realized that
I was kind of fond of the title.

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:55.450
And the title in this case,
in the case of this book,

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:59.900
really refers to basically,
you know,

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:03.360
the days that you don't
notice going by

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:07.580
and in retrospect are really
the most important ones,

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:11.110
the ones that make up
the bulk of our lives.

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:13.550
I don't know, I just think
in terms of bright --

00:05:13.550 --> 00:05:19.190
I think my characters are attracted
to New York like moths to flame.

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:22.410
I think that's part of it.

00:05:22.410 --> 00:05:26.550
I like the word in so far

00:05:26.550 --> 00:05:31.280
as it denotes intelligence
and illumination.

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:34.210
I don't know.

00:05:34.210 --> 00:05:38.830
I'm going to try and stay away
from it for the next few titles.

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:41.940
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Well, the other thing,
so as I was talking about - -

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:45.350
