00:42:30.430 --> 00:42:34.140
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline: How did
I start my own book?

00:42:34.140 --> 00:42:37.370
I've known I wanted to be
a writer since I was seven.

00:42:37.370 --> 00:42:39.910
And I talk about it in
Brown Girl Dreaming.

00:42:39.910 --> 00:42:41.980
I got in trouble for lying a lot,

00:42:41.980 --> 00:42:44.100
and I had a teacher
who said write it down.

00:42:44.100 --> 00:42:50.330
And it was such a strong -- I
was constantly making up stories,

00:42:50.330 --> 00:42:54.210
but I was also bored a lot.

00:42:54.210 --> 00:42:55.870
I think that's the difference

00:42:55.870 --> 00:42:59.810
between my kids and
who is was as a kid.

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:03.270
We had commercials, television
went off at six o'clock

00:43:03.270 --> 00:43:04.580
and then the news came on.

00:43:04.580 --> 00:43:05.880
We had three channels.

00:43:05.880 --> 00:43:07.640
So there were all these places.

00:43:07.640 --> 00:43:09.730
I was in houses of worship a lot,

00:43:09.730 --> 00:43:11.610
so there were a lot
of places to be bored.

00:43:11.610 --> 00:43:16.830
[Laughter] And I would make
up stories and I would write.

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:18.780
And I just kept doing it.

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:21.040
I didn't know that it
would eventually be this.

00:43:21.040 --> 00:43:25.040
But I knew that I needed to
do it for my own salvation.

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:26.660
&gt;&gt; Leigh: When did you
start writing it down?

00:43:26.660 --> 00:43:28.390
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline: When I was seven.

00:43:28.390 --> 00:43:30.300
When I learned how to write my name

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:33.730
from that point I realized how
powerful putting letters together

00:43:33.730 --> 00:43:36.110
and words together and
words making sentences

00:43:36.110 --> 00:43:37.750
and sentences making paragraphs.

00:43:37.750 --> 00:43:42.290
Like that was mind blowing to
me that it was just that simple.

00:43:42.290 --> 00:43:46.540
And that what was in my head
I could actually put on paper

00:43:46.540 --> 00:43:47.840
and it could be something.

00:43:47.840 --> 00:43:50.050
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Do you want
to be a writer?

00:43:50.050 --> 00:43:51.350
&gt;&gt; Yes. [Applause]

00:43:51.350 --> 00:43:53.650
&gt;&gt; Jay: Stick with it.

00:43:55.960 --> 00:44:00.450
&gt;&gt; Hi, this is for Jay.

00:44:00.450 --> 00:44:04.290
I know you're very renowned
as a Manhattan writer.

00:44:04.290 --> 00:44:07.500
But I have to take issue with
the first thing you said.

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:08.800
&gt;&gt; Jay: Uh-oh.

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:10.810
&gt;&gt; Of your description
of Manhattan in the 80s.

00:44:10.810 --> 00:44:15.560
I've lived in Manhattan all
through for about 40 years.

00:44:15.560 --> 00:44:18.920
And I raised a child in the
80s on the upper west side,

00:44:18.920 --> 00:44:22.610
and your description is
totally unrecognizable to me.

00:44:22.610 --> 00:44:24.950
There were no crack vials
I was stepping over.

00:44:24.950 --> 00:44:30.050
I mean a gross generalization of
what was a problem in New York.

00:44:30.050 --> 00:44:31.720
&gt;&gt; Jay: Well, there
were these pockets --

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:33.290
&gt;&gt; Yes, of course.

00:44:33.290 --> 00:44:36.610
&gt;&gt; Jay: There were these pockets of
civilization, the upper west side

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:42.450
and the upper east side were these
long- established residential areas

00:44:42.450 --> 00:44:44.370
where families were raised.

00:44:44.370 --> 00:44:45.720
But around the edges --

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:47.310
&gt;&gt; Of course, I wouldn't
disagree with that.

00:44:47.310 --> 00:44:50.130
&gt;&gt; Jay: And for that matter
Amsterdam Avenue and Needle Park

00:44:50.130 --> 00:44:54.850
on the upper west side
when I arrived in New York

00:44:54.850 --> 00:44:56.150
in the early 80s it was

00:44:56.150 --> 00:44:58.740
like Amsterdam Avenue
was almost uncrossable.

00:44:58.740 --> 00:45:00.250
It was pretty dangerous.

00:45:00.250 --> 00:45:05.020
&gt;&gt; I cross it every day.

00:45:05.020 --> 00:45:08.300
&gt;&gt; Leigh: One little girl,
this is our last question.

00:45:08.300 --> 00:45:12.100
&gt;&gt; Jay: Last question.

00:45:12.100 --> 00:45:15.250
&gt;&gt; Can I make this shorter?

00:45:15.250 --> 00:45:20.680
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Just bend
it down towards you.

00:45:20.680 --> 00:45:21.980
What's your name?

00:45:21.980 --> 00:45:23.280
&gt;&gt; My name is Margaret.

00:45:23.280 --> 00:45:24.580
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Hi, Margaret.

00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:27.180
&gt;&gt; And this is for Mrs. Woodson.

00:45:27.180 --> 00:45:30.250
What's your favorite medium
like when you're writing.

00:45:30.250 --> 00:45:32.970
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline: Thanks for
your question, Margaret.

00:45:32.970 --> 00:45:35.740
And I love that you
adjusted the mic first.

00:45:35.740 --> 00:45:39.030
I usually start writing by hand.

00:45:39.030 --> 00:45:42.200
And when the ideas start coming
fast I move to the computer,

00:45:42.200 --> 00:45:44.600
and then I go back
to writing by hand.

00:45:44.600 --> 00:45:47.260
So I go back and forth.

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:49.460
Just because I always have
a pad and a pen somewhere,

00:45:49.460 --> 00:45:52.910
and I write on my hand sometimes.

00:45:52.910 --> 00:45:55.120
I don't have any today.

00:45:55.120 --> 00:45:57.870
Today is a bust.

00:45:57.870 --> 00:46:01.690
But, yeah, I have a
ton of pens right now.

00:46:01.690 --> 00:46:07.130
So, yeah, by hand and then I have
a laptop that I carry everywhere.

00:46:07.130 --> 00:46:10.690
Viking will be able
to tell you that.

00:46:10.690 --> 00:46:11.990
So thank you.

00:46:11.990 --> 00:46:13.290
Thanks, everyone.

00:46:13.290 --> 00:46:14.590
&gt;&gt; Leigh: Thanks very much.

00:46:14.590 --> 00:46:15.890
&gt;&gt; Jay: Thank you.

